Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

There are commercial options to return to the UK.
On 28 April, the UK will also operate a special flight from Manila to London, with feeder flights from Iloilo, Tacloban and Davao and coaches across mainland Luzon.
Commercial flights
There remains widespread disruption to international travel routes, and domestic flights are currently suspended.
The following airlines are operating international flights from Manila Ninoy Aquino International Airport with connections to the UK:
Qatar Airways to London Heathrow, Manchester and Edinburgh, via Doha
Korean Air to London Heathrow, via Seoul Incheon
Gulf Air to London Heathrow, via Bahrain
You will need to pay for your return travel to the UK. If departure options are available but you cannot afford the travel costs and have exhausted all other options for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan from the government. This is a last resort option and you would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK. For more information, you should contact Corporate Travel Management (CTM). CTM are a commercial partner of the FCO and are authorised to administer such loans on behalf of the FCO.
Travel to departure airports for commercial flights
Resolution No.15 of the Philippines Inter-Agency Task Force grants that all stranded foreign nationals can travel to and from national government facilities such as airports, ferries, bus terminals etc.
If you plan to take a commercial flight but are experiencing difficulty travelling to the airport due to community quarantine restrictions, the British Embassy can provide a letter to facilitate your passage through checkpoints.
Contact the British Embassy Manila at ukinthephilippines@fco.gov.uk. You can also seek assistance from your local Department of Tourism office, which may be able to offer advice on transport options or hotels.
UK special flights
On 28 April, the UK will operate special flights from Iloilo, Cebu, Tacloban and Davao to Manila, and coaches across mainland Luzon. These operate before a special flight from Manila to London for British tourists, short term visitors and their direct dependants to return to the UK.
the cost of the journey is £800 per person
to be eligible for this flight, you must be normally resident in the UK. Eligibility will be checked before tickets are issued
If you wish to travel, register for tickets on the CTM website as soon as possible. Tickets will not be on sale at the airport. Do not travel to the airport without a confirmed ticket.
To make a booking, you will need:
full passport and contact details for each traveller you are registering
your UK home address and postcode
your means of payment, such as credit or debit card details
If you have difficulty booking online, send an SMS text message with your full name to the CTM team on +44 (0) 786-009-3016, and their team will contact you to provide assistance.
If you cannot pay the cost of the ticket, send an SMS with your full name to the CTM team on +44 (0)7537 416 127 and their team will contact you to provide assistance. If you have exhausted all other options available to you for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan from the government to cover the cost of the ticket. You would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK. CTM is a commercial partner of the FCO and authorised to administer such loans on behalf of the FCO.
You may find it helpful to read our guide to eligibility and the booking process for special charter flights.
Travel to departure airports for UK special flights
The British Embassy Manila is working with the Department of Transport and local authorities to identify transport options for those with confirmed bookings to access airports.
You should note that:
the Embassy may need to share your contact and location details with the Philippines Department of Tourism, and Local Government Units. If you would like to return to the UK on these flights, but do not wish for your information to be shared, notify the Embassy via ukinthephilippines@fco.gov.uk.
once flight bookings are confirmed by CTM, you will receive a letter from the British Embassy confirming your right to travel to access these flights. You should carry this letter when you travel.
using a face mask or an improvised face covering (e.g. do-it-yourself mask, handkerchief, scarf to cover nose and mouth) is now mandatory in many areas in the Philippines
Check the information below on steps you need to take to prepare for your journey to your departure airport.
To reach Davao airport
The Department of Tourism (DoT) and provincial tourism offices are facilitating overnight van transfers from the following locations for confirmed ticket holders (timings TBC):
Cagayan de Oro
Cotabato, General Santos, Sultan Kudarat
Surigao (and Caraga region – Region XIII)
Davao Province (taxis are available within Davao City)
To arrange this transport, contact the relevant DoT official. They can also provide information on any costs associated with the route you are offered.
If you need transport from a different location in Mindanao, contact the British Embassy. We are working to identify other transport options.
When travelling, you should note that:
you will need your passport, flight itinerary and Embassy letter to cross the border into Davao
you do not need medical clearance to enter Davao, but there may be medical certificate requirements in your departure area. This applies in the Caraga region. Check with the DoT contacts above for more information and help arranging these.
To reach Iloilo airport
The Department of Tourism (DoT) and provincial tourism offices have identified the following transport routes for confirmed ticket holders (timings TBC):
Boracay – boat and land transport (details TBC)
Bacolod – chartered ferry to Iloilo (likely to be at 2.30am on 28 April), then bus transfer to Iloilo airport
Dumaguete – land transfer to Bacolod (details TBC) to join the Bacolod leg
Siquijor – ferry to Dumaguete (details TBC) to join the Dumaguete leg
To arrange a place on the transport, contact the relevant Department of Tourism or provincial tourism official. Medical clearances will be required, the DoT will also advise you on this.
To reach Tacloban airport
Contact the Department of Tourism (DoT) local contact for assistance in arranging transport to Tacloban airport.
To reach Cebu airport
Contact the Department of Tourism (DoT) local contact for assistance in arranging transport to Cebu airport. Medical certificates are not required for departing passengers.
If you plan to make your own way to the airport, check this list of car and van rental companies.
To reach Manila airport from Luzon
Buses will operate from across Luzon, with collections planned from the following locations:
Western Luzon: Baguio, La Union, Pangasinan, Tarlac
Central Luzon: Aurora, Nueva Ecija, Bulacan, Bataan, Zambales, Pampanga, Rizal
Southern Luzon: Batangas, Laguna, Cavite
South-eastern Luzon: Bicol, Masbate, Camarines Sur, Quezon
Eastern Luzon: Cagayan, Isabela, Nueva Vizcaya, Abra, Quirino
To arrange bus travel, email the British Embassy Manila at ukinthephilippines@fco.gov.uk with the subject line “Luzon Bus Travel Request”. In your email, provide the full names of all travellers in your group, and details of your location. You must have a seat confirmed on the 28 April special flight to be able to access these buses. Finalised routes and pick-up locations will be confirmed at a later date.
If you plan to make your own way to the airport, check this list of car and van rental companies.
However you travel, note that there are medical certificate requirements for travel in some regions and provinces in mainland Luzon:
check the table below for information on certificate requirements in each area
if you need a medical certificate, apply as soon as possible at the local/city/regional health centre.
applications should be quick but may depend on the availability of the issuing doctor. Department of Tourism local co-ordinators can assist in securing certificates.
even where a certificate is not required, you should still carry your flight itinerary and the letter which you will receive from the Embassy to assist you at checkpoints.
Region Medical certificate required?
Northwest Luzon (Ilocos Norte, Ilocos Sur, La Union and Pangasinan) Yes, fee between PHP 100-300
North-east Luzon (Batanes, the valley provinces of Cagayan, Isabela, Nueva Vizcaya, and Quirino) Yes, free of charge
Central Luzon (Aurora, Bataan, Bulacan, Nueva Ecija, Pampanga, Tarlac and Zambales) No
Southern Luzon (Batangas, Cavite, Laguna, Rizal, Quezon Province) No
Bicol Region (Albay, Camarines Norte, Camarines Sur, Catanduanes, Masbate, and Sorsogon) No
National Capital Region (Caloocan, Las Piñas, Makati, Malabon, Manila, Mandaluyong, Marikina, Muntinlupa, Navotas, Parañaque, Pasay, Pasig, Pateros, Quezon City, San Juan, Taguig and Valenzuela) No
Cordillera Administrative Region (Abra, Apayao, Baguio, Benguet, Ifugao, Kalinga, Mountain Province) No
Arrival in the UK
When you arrive back in the UK, follow the guidance for when you return to the UK on steps you should take to protect yourself and others.
Future options
The British Embassy Manila is in contact with airlines, the Philippine authorities and other governments to make sure commercial options for returning to the UK remain open for as long as possible.
Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British Embassy on Twitter and Facebook.
If you cannot leave the Philippines at this time, you should:
contact the Embassy at ukinthephilippines@fco.gov.uk to inform them of your details and current situation
continue to follow advice and guidance issued by national and local government units.
continue to monitor this page, and the Embassy’s social media for further updates
See more information and advice about staying where you are if you cannot return to the UK.
Further information
See additional advice on making travel plans to return to the UK, or what to do if you cannot depart immediately.
